**Answer: B -- Adiabatic is steeper**

For an isothermal process: PV = C, so \frac{dP}{dV} = -\frac{P}{V}

For an adiabatic process: PV^{\gamma} = C, so \frac{dP}{dV} = -\gamma\frac{P}{V}

Since \gamma > 1, the adiabatic slope is \gamma times the isothermal slope at any point.

This means the adiabatic curve is always steeper than the isothermal curve on the P-V diagram.

**Answer: B -- 2v**

The speed of sound in an ideal gas is:
v_s = \sqrt{\frac{\gamma RT}{M}}

So v_s \propto \sqrt{T}

\frac{v_2}{v_1} = \sqrt{\frac{T_2}{T_1}} = \sqrt{\frac{4T}{T}} = 2

Therefore v_2 = 2v. The speed of sound doubles when the absolute temperature is quadrupled.
